snippet.textDisplay:
I keep seeing y'all weld, and while I'm sure it holds and does the job, I keep seeing just a small thing y'all can do to help keep yer weld steady. Marty, anchor yourself bro. I see you out there floating around with the TIG torch somewhere in outer space. Just... take yer pinky finger on your torch hand, set it on your piece and work that way. Keeps you steady mate. Your torch stays at a more normalized distance from the piece, you don't have to worry about long arcing that boye which means your heat stays more constant and is easier to control, and then you don't cook the everloving chromium out of your pretty stainless whatevers. This doesn't work well at all if you're trying to throw down a pass around the whole pipe in one go, but if that's not your goal, give it a shot, see if you like it. I do see you doing that on the bung weld in this video, which is great. My only suggestion there is that with your wrist being on the vice might limit your motion going around such a tiny piece.

As an aside, you could also bend over or find a stool, prop yer elbow on something, and only move your forearm. The steadier you are, the easier it is to throw down a decent weld. Get anchored before you get into freehanding your goodies.


Also, its your cars, your channel, your money. I can absolutely just go fuck myself.

-Sincerely, a halfway decent welder who almost knows what they're doing
